If I read that quote, knowing what I know of Jefferson, I think he is talking about fearing how the citizens will react if they don't, in state manners, have an allegiance to a G-d who dishes out justice and wrath. I don't think of it as a flattering statement, but rather a kind of snarky one aimed at believers. I think that's what he was fearful of, not an actual G-d of some sort.<br>
<br>
I also don't think of Andrew Johnson as a Founding Father, seeing as her was president nearly one hundred years after the Revolutionary War, but hey, I guess that's just me.<br>
<br>
And the quotes by Washington illuminating his lack of interest in religion far outnumber any religious quotes.<br>
