<br>
Torquemada was exercising his religion when he impaled, burned, quartered, drowned, and beheadded all the victims of his inquisition.  His god (ironicly the same one you worship) demanded the death of the infidels.<br>
<br>
The founding fathers were of a diverse background.  You may find several held close ideals about god, but again, they were fleeing various persecutions when they left europe (at the hands of xians mind you) and didn't want it repeated here.  Most of them were deists, not xian; some were atheist, not xian; of the few xians, some xians did not recognize the other xians as xian.  Furthermore, they wrote extensively and spoke frequently.  Were I to address a religous group, I would speak in religous terms and descriptions.  It is simple sense in communicating a message to use what is most easily communicated.  <br>
<br>
However, just like DAG and his Einstien theism fantasy, you have to take the entire body of their record and look at it as a whole.  Out of context many things can be colored to hold a religous halo, no matter where they began.  Surely you recognize this in the use of biblical quotes to back spurrious claims.  You go read the whole verse, not just the line to see what the message really is.  None of your quotes (Aside from the obvious last one) distinguish the god cited as the xian one.  Few of the quotes even mention god (providence is infact fate, fortune or good luck) so it is a tenuous rationalization at best.<br>
<br>
Irrespective of the messages you choose to take, their other writings are very clear about the matter.  No gov't sponsering of religion.  Period.  He is living in  a house I am paying for, he is drawing a check out of my wallet, he should damn well have the respect for his fellow americans to be curteous.  If he wants to preach, go get ordained an become a minister.  Standing at a podium holding your religeon above all others in the world is not the highest form of religous freedom, it is the losest form of disrespect and abuse of power.<br>
